'''Séraphin "Séra" Martin''' (2 July 1906 – 23 April 1993) was a [[France|French]] [[Middle-distance running|middle-distance runner]] who set [[List of world records in athletics|world records]] in the [[800 metres]] and [[1000 metres world record progression|1000 metres]]. He competed at the 1928 and 1932 Olympics and placed sixth and eighth in the 800 metres, respectively.

==Career==

Martin set a [[List of world records in athletics|world record]] at [[1000 metres]] in 1926, running 2:26.8 to break [[Sven Lundgren]]'s old record of 2:28.6.<ref name="butler">{{citation |author1=Butler, Mark |author2=IAAF Media & Public Relations Department |publisher=[[International Association of Athletics Federations]] |title=IAAF Statistics Handbook Daegu 2011 |year=2011}}</ref> Two weeks before the [[1928 Summer Olympics]], Martin ran [[800 metres]] in 1:50.6, breaking [[Otto Peltzer]]'s world record by a full second.<ref name="butler"/>{{#tag:ref|The qualitative difference between these records was much smaller. Peltzer's time of 1:51.6 was set at 880 yards and was roughly equivalent to 1:50.9 for 800 metres.<ref name="jukola"/><ref name="otto">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/pe/otto-peltzer-1.html |title=Otto Peltzer Bio, Stats and Results |publisher=Sports Reference LLC |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref>|group="note"}} This established him as one of the favourites for the [[1928 Summer Olympics|Olympics]] in [[Amsterdam]].<ref name="jukola"/><ref name="sr">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1928/ATH/mens-800-metres.html |title=Athletics at the 1928 Amsterdam Summer Games: Men's 800 metres |publisher=Sports Reference LLC |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> He did make the [[Athletics at the 1928 Summer Olympics &ndash; Men's 800 metres|Olympic final]], but was never a major factor in the race<ref name="jukola"/> and finished sixth in a time of 1:54.6,<ref name="srsm">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/sera-martin-1.html |title=Séra Martin Bio, Stats and Results |publisher=Sports Reference LLC |accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> clearly slower than the 1:53.0 he ran in the semi-finals.<ref name="srsm"/>

He returned to the Olympics in [[1932 Summer Olympics|1932]], placing eighth with a time of 1:53.6.<ref name="srsm"/> Martin was one of the [[Pacemaker (running)|pacemakers]] when [[Jules Ladoumègue]] set his world record at [[1500 metres]].<ref name="jukola">{{cite book |title=Huippu-urheilun historia |year=1935 |publisher=[[Werner Söderström Osakeyhtiö]] |author=Jukola, Martti |language=Finnish}}</ref>

